│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                            │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `loop-unroll-full` pass is causing a miscompilation by incorrectly peeling a loop. The │
│ `Alive2` tool shows that the transformed code returns `null` instead of a pointer to a     │
│ global variable. This points to an error in how values, particularly from PHI nodes, are   │
│ handled during the peeling process.                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `opt` log indicates that `ScalarEvolution` correctly identifies the loop's trip count, │
│ and the unroller decides to peel one iteration. The transformation is performed by         │
│ `llvm::peelLoop`. The key problem is visible in the generated IR for the peeled iteration: │
│ ```llvm                                                                                    │
│ cleanup.peel:                                                                              │
│   %retval.2.peel = phi ptr [ undef, %for.body.peel ], [ @GlobIntONE,                       │
│ %cleanup.loopexit.peel ]                                                                   │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│ In the peeled iteration, the loop condition is constant `true`, making the path from       │
│ `%cleanup.loopexit.peel` to `%cleanup.peel` unreachable. However, the PHI node             │
│ `%retval.2.peel` incorrectly includes an incoming value from this dead path. This prevents │
│ proper simplification and leads to `undef` (`null`) being propagated as the function's     │
│ return value.                                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root of the problem is in the `peelLoop` function in `LoopPeel.cpp`. When cloning the  │
│ original loop body to create the peeled iteration, the logic for cloning PHI nodes is      │
│ flawed. It iterates over all incoming values of an original PHI node and adds a            │
│ corresponding remapped entry to the new PHI in the peeled block.                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ The bug is that this process does not verify if the predecessor block for an incoming      │
│ value is actually part of the set of blocks being peeled. In this case, the PHI            │
│ `%retval.2` has an incoming value from `%cleanup.loopexit`. The cloning logic sees this,   │
│ remaps `%cleanup.loopexit` to `%cleanup.loopexit.peel`, and adds `[ @GlobIntONE,           │
│ %cleanup.loopexit.peel ]` to the new PHI, `%retval.2.peel`. It fails to recognize that     │
│ this edge is internal to the loop and should only be considered if the predecessor is also │
│ part of the same peeled iteration. Because the control flow within the peeled iteration    │
│ makes this path impossible, this PHI entry is incorrect and should not have been added.    │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to add a check within the PHI cloning loop in `peelLoop`. Before adding an      │
│ incoming value to the new PHI, we must verify that the original predecessor block is one   │
│ of the blocks that was cloned for the peeled iteration.                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix should be applied in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp` inside the           │
│ `peelLoop` function, within the loop that populates the new PHI nodes.                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp:580                                              │
│ // Inside the loop `for (unsigned i = 0, e = OrigPN->getNumIncomingValues(); ...`          │
│                                                                                            │
│ // The original code is:                                                                   │
│ // NewPN->addIncoming(V, BB);                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ // It should be changed to:                                                                │
│ if (PeeledBBs.count(OrigPN->getIncomingBlock(i)))                                          │
│   NewPN->addIncoming(V, BB);                                                               │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ This change ensures that we only add incoming values to the peeled PHI node if the         │
│ corresponding predecessor block is also part of the peeled iteration. This correctly       │
│ prunes the infeasible edge from `%cleanup.loopexit.peel`, preventing the bug.              │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The miscompilation is caused by a bug in `peelLoop` where it creates an invalid PHI node   │
│ by including an incoming value from a path that is unreachable within the peeled           │
│ iteration. By adding a check to ensure that a PHI's incoming value only comes from a block │
│ that is also part of the peeled iteration, we can fix the incorrect PHI construction and   │
│ resolve the bug. This ensures that the semantics of the program are preserved after        │
│ peeling.                                                                                   │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
│                                                                                            │
