│ An LLVM bug in the `loop-unroll-full` pass is causing a miscompilation when peeling loops  │
│ with complex control flow. The issue stems from the `peelLoop` function, which incorrectly │
│ constructs PHI nodes in the peeled iteration.                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ When cloning the loop body, the existing logic remaps all incoming values for a PHI node   │
│ without verifying if the corresponding predecessor block is part of the peeled iteration.  │
│ This can lead to the creation of PHI entries for infeasible paths, where the control flow  │
│ within the peeled iteration makes an edge unreachable. In the provided reproducer, this    │
│ results in an `undef` value being propagated through a PHI, ultimately causing the         │
│ function to return `null` instead of the correct pointer value.                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to add a check within the PHI cloning logic in `peelLoop`. Before adding an     │
│ incoming value to a new PHI node in the peeled block, we must ensure that the original     │
│ predecessor block is also one of the blocks being peeled. This prevents the creation of    │
│ invalid PHI entries from unreachable predecessors.                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ This patch applies the necessary check, ensuring that the semantics of the program are     │
│ preserved after loop peeling.                                                              │
